<B><FONT SIZE=5><P ALIGN="CENTER">Arithmetic Progressions</P>
</B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>
</FONT><B><FONT SIZE=4><P ALIGN="CENTER">Learning Plan 1</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"></P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER">Introduction</P>
</FONT><FONT SIZE=5>
</B></FONT><P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>A sequence is said to be an arithmetic progression if the sequence can be written in such a way that the difference between successive numbers is constant.   This constant difference is called the common difference.</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>
<B><FONT SIZE=4><P>Example 1</P>
</B></FONT>
<P>The sequence</P>

<P>2, 4, 6, 8, 10, 12, 14, ……..</P>

<P>is an arithmetic progression or an arithmetic sequence because the difference between successive terms is 2.</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>
<B><FONT SIZE=4><P>Example 2</P>
</B></FONT>
<P>The sequence </P>

<P>12, 17, 22, 27, 32, ……</P>

<P>is an arithmetic progression with a common difference of 5.</P>
